The Federal Government has perfected plans to roll out new Compressed Natural Gas, CNG initiative next month. The government said the programme is a critical requirement precedent to full deregulation in Nigeria. It has therefore, concluded discussions with Original Equipment Manufacturers, OEMs, to supply needed parts to facilitate roll out of the program, Minister of State for Petroleum Resources, Timipre Sylva, said at a recent meeting with Major Oil Marketers Association of Nigeria (MOMAN) and Depot and Petroleum Products Marketers Association of Nigeria (DAPPMAN) How To Stop Soot Pollution ‘How Oil Production Underperformance Is Affecting Nigeria,… Urging them to pave way for the installation of gas dispensing stations within their premises, the minister said government has arranged with OEMs to make their facilities available in partnership with the marketers. He said: “See how you can link up with some of these OEMs so that you will be part of this. This programme is supposed to kick-start what we want to start in March. So, we don’t have too much time but we don’t want to go further without carrying you along. “So, this is part of what we want to put in place with the structure what to put in place before this is part of the building block towards deregulation, because these things have to be in place so that people at least can have an alternative.” He disclosed that the OEMs are expected to provide 50 per cent of funding while the Federal Government put in place the 50 per cent balance.